Interface IPriorityQueue<E extends java.lang.Comparable<? super E>>

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IQueue<E>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    Heap
    public interface IPriorityQueue<E extends java.lang.Comparable<? super E>>
extends IQueue<E>
    A priority queue is different from a regular queue because it respects priority among the elements. The head of a priority queue is an element of greatest priority among all elements within the queue. The queue retrieval operations poll, remove, peek, and element access the element at the head of the queue.

        E poll()
        Retrieves and removes an element of greatest priority, which is the head of the priority queue. For example: A queue that prioritizes Strings by max length would return the longest String. A queue that prioritizes Integers by min value would return the minimum number.
